  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Multipurpose Small Dams</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The anticipated beneficiary groups and benefits of this project will include the following: (i) Key government authorities concerned with small dams development (The Ministry of Lands, Energy and Water Development and its Department of Water Affairs; the Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives; Ministry of Tourism, Environment and Natural Resources and its Environmental Council of Zambia); (ii) Some 40,000 people who benefitting from 4 dams (1 new constructed and 3 rehabilitated) during the course of the field testing; (iii) Some 50,000 people will benefit from 5 dams that will be designed for investment by others partners; (iv) Local entrepreneurs, water services providers, small scale farmers and small scale economic actors depending on water; (v) Private sector actors engaged in water infrastructure development; (vi) People in other communities who will benefitting from long-term up-scaling under the IWRM/WE towards 2030; (vii) Bi- and multi-lateral development cooperation partners and national/international investors; (viii) Associations such as Public-private partnerships (PPP),Coffee Growers&#x2019; Association of Zambia (ZGCA), the Zambia Export Growers&#x2019; Association and the Conservation Farming Unit (CFU); (ix) University of Zambia (UNZA); and (x) Consultants and advisors involved in designing the construction and operation of the next generation of dams in Africa and globally.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The objective of the Project is to upgrade and carry out field testing of national guidelines for community driven planning, design and implementation of multi-purpose small dams in Zambia, Such guidelines are essential to effectively guide GRZ in engaging with external support partners to accelerate the investments in multi-purpose small dams for improved water security in the country. Thus the project will add significant value to the strategic up-scaling of dam development and contribute to the attainment of the MDG goals and the ambitions of the Africa Water Vision. The Project will contribute to design planning and funds mobilisation to spur new and on-going water development programmes such as the Integrated Water Resources Management and Water Efficiency Implementation Plan (2007-30). The project also involves direct investments in connection with the field testing of the guidelines that will include rehabilitation and rehabilitation of three existing dams and construction of one new small dam directly benefitting some 40,000 people.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The objective of the project is to develop and field test guidelines for community driven planning, design and implementation of multi-purpose small dams. The purpose of the guidelines is to provide guidance and demonstration of their use to support the efforts of the central and local authorities and financial partners in the development of small multi-purpose dams.</narrative>
  </description>
